## Git Workflow

These rules apply to all repos unless a project CLAUDE.md explicitly overrides them.

### Branching
- `main` is always deployable / stable
- All work happens on feature branches: `feature/<short-description>`
- Bug fixes: `fix/<short-description>`
- Experimental / exploratory: `experiment/<short-description>`

### Commits
- Do not ever use "git add -A" or "git add ."; rather, specifically add files by name
  to avoid snarfing up unexpected files in the repo
- Commit early and often — small, focused commits preferred over large ones
- Commit message format: imperative mood, present tense
  - Good: `Add CEFR level selector to config panel`
  - Bad: `Added stuff`, `WIP`, `fix`
- Never commit directly to `main`
- Always run tests before committing (see TDD section below)

### Standard flow for a feature
```bash
git checkout -b feature/<name>
# ... work, test, iterate ...
git add -p                    # stage hunks interactively, not whole files blindly
git commit -m "<message>"
git push origin feature/<name>
# open PR / merge to main when ready
```

### Before merging to main
- All tests pass
- No debug artifacts (console.log spam, commented-out code blocks, TODO bombs)
- DECISIONS.md updated if any architectural choices were made

